Sooooo Melanoma happened. 

The last few months have been a bit scary. We discovered the little b*tch Melly on my shoulder back in August and have been going through the gauntlet of doctors visits and tons of tests. Ended up having to have surgery to remove a big chunk of skin on my shoulder as well as remove a few lymph nodes from under my arm pit for testing. I’m happy to report the surgery was successful in removing all the dangerous cells. 

The whole thing was pretty unexpected. Gotta admit, I take really good care of my skin and wear sunscreen like it’s going out of style.. yet here we are. 

I’m posting this because skin cancer can be pretty deadly, and yet preventable, if caught early enough. I would highly recommend keeping a close eye on all your moles, spots & freckles that change shape, color, texture or become asymmetrical. Doesn’t hurt to get them checked out if you’re ever in doubt. 

Big shout out to my wife, dermatologist, nurses, surgeon and plastic surgeon who took such good care of me… and a special shout out to my brother in law @dhuczneker for telling me to go get my funky mole checked out in the first place.  So happy to be closing this chapter on this. 🙏🏼❤️

Health Update: 

I’ve got a bunch of people asking how the hell I’m at BravoCon after major surgery. The surgery itself was 3 weeks ago. I was waiting on the test results before saying anything publicly. 

Everything is healing up nicely. Here’s how the incision sites are looking now. I still have a lot of swelling at the site where they took out the lymph nodes under my arm. That causes most of the discomfort. The cut on my shoulder just feels so tight from pulling the skin together. Half the stitches were already removed. Lots of tingling and weird skin sensations as the nerves heal. But with all that said, Doctors are really happy with the progress. 

And for everyone wanting to know what the mole looked like before it was removed… I’m working on getting a pic from my dermatologist. So once I get it, I’ll share. 

Also, I love hearing how many people are scheduling appts to get their skin checked out. I can’t stress the importance of that. Catching it early saved my life.

#melanoma #melanomaawareness
